Collection Name: CU Museum of Natural History: Earl Morris papers
Title: Field Notes: Expedition to Canyon del Muerto, Arizona
Name: Morris, Earl Halstead, 1889-1956
Abstract: This diary is possibly authored by A. V. Kidder. Daily entries describe work done primarily at Mummy Cave, Massacre Cave, Tse-a-ha-tso Cave, and Sliding Rock House. A note on the title page reads, "See original notebook for accompanying sketches." The original notebook in reference is not in this collection. The diary also makes frequent reference to the maps of Raymond Emerson, party surveyor. These are also not in the collection.

Collection Name: CU Museum of Natural History: Earl Morris papers
Title: Transcript, Field notebooks
Name: Morris, Earl Halstead, 1889-1956
Abstract: This typescript copy includes the period covered by the handwritten diary books (EHM02.04_007_003) from which it was derived. During the period of September 17 to October 7, Morris and crew restored the tower at Mummy Cave, Canyon del Muerto. The journal describes these activities and also interactions with visitors including A. V. Kidder. From October 13 to November 4, Earl H. Morris and field crew conducted excavations to the north of Gallup and in the Bennett's Peak area. The primary objective of excavations in this area was to collect charred timber for dendrochronological analysis by A. E. Douglass. In addition, the team excavated many burials and grave goods were sent, at least in part, to the University of New Mexico. An inventory of these materials can be found in item EHM02.04_007_006.
Note: Pages 34-69 of the online, publicly available version of this document have been redacted to protect sensitive information. A full copy is available on request.

Collection Name: CU Museum of Natural History: Earl Morris papers
Title: Portraits and personal interest: Portraits
Name: Morris, Earl Halstead, 1889-1956
Abstract: This file contains individual and group portraits both candid and staged. Those pictured are primarily archaeologists and their families. These individuals were consistently photographed outdoors either visiting a site of excavation or at another semi-professional gathering, possibly including the first annual Pecos Conference in 1927. There are also a number of pictures of individuals hailing from tribes in the Southwest including Navajo Nation, the Zuni tribe, Hopi tribe, and, possibly, from Pueblos which are as yet unidentified. The series of photographs of men and women in formal wear posed in rocky landscapes may originate from a location near Boulder, Colorado.

Collection Name: CU Museum of Natural History: Earl Morris papers
Title: Portraits and personal interest: Scenes and objects
Name: Morris, Earl Halstead, 1889-1956
Abstract: This file contains images that depict landscapes, buildings, interiors, cultural objects, and activities. The images vary widely in terms of subject and geographical area. Larger groups of photographs document a dance at Kewa (Santa Domingo) Pueblo, sandpainting by Navajo men, a rattlesnake, images of areas around Boulder and the University of Colorado, Scott Morris' pottery collection, and two of Earl Morris' commemorative medals.
